cs.CR, cs.DB, cs.CY, cs.GR, cs.SI

This paper discusses the use of geo-indistinguishability, a formal notion of privacy for location-based systems, to add noise to published spatial data. This topic falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) as it deals with protecting sensitive information from potential threats. Additionally, the use of spatial data and databases is also relevant to the sub-categories of databases (cs.DB) and cyber-physical systems (cs.CY). The paper also discusses the tradeoff between privacy and data utility, which is a common theme in the sub-category of graphics (cs.GR). Finally, the use of algorithms and techniques to add noise to data is relevant to the sub-category of signal processing (cs.SI).
